@node PQU "Foundation: Physical Quantities and Units"
· All quantities in physics consist of a numerical magnitude and a unit.  All units can be expressed in terms of the SI base units:

Mass:                Kilogram (kg)
Length:              Metre (m)
Time:                Second (s)
Current:             Ampere (A)
Temperature:         Kelvin (K)     temperature/K = temperature/°C + 273
Amount of substance: Mole (mol)

· If you expand the units for each term of an equation in terms of the base units, you can check whether an equation is balanced (homogeneous).

· Instead of ×10¬ you can use:

 prefix     x

atto  (a): -18
femto (f): -15
pico  (p): -12
nano  (n): -9
micro (µ): -6
milli (m): -3
centi (c): -2
deci  (d): -1
kilo  (k):  3
mega  (M):  6
giga  (G):  9
tera  (T):  12

· When dealing with quantities of atoms and molecules, it is conventional to measure mass and number relative to carbon-12 atom.

· The relative molecular mass of a substance is the mass of a molecule of a substance divided by 1/12 the mass of a carbon-12 atom

» Moles = @{u}         Mass          @{uu}
          Relative Molecular Mass

» Atoms = Moles × Avogadro's Number (6.02 × 10²³)

· The mole is the amount of substance containing the same number of @{"atoms" link Atom} or molecules as the number of atoms in 0.012 kg of carbon-12.  This number of atoms is called the Avogadro constant, L=6.02×10²³ mol-¹

· Scalar quantities have magnitude only:

length, speed, mass, density, energy, power, temperature, charge and potential difference.

· Vector quantities have a direction:

displacement, force, torque, velocity, acceleration, momentum, electric current and electric field.

· To add vectors, draw them in a line.  The line joining start directly to finish is the resultant.
@endnode

@node Kine "Foundation: Kinematics"

· Equations:

» Average Velocity = @{u}displacement@{uu}
                         time

» Acceleration = @{u}change in velocity@{uu}
                        time

· Equations of motion:

where @{b}u@{ub}=initial velocity
      @{b}v@{ub}=final velocity
      @{b}s@{ub}=displacement
      @{b}t@{ub}=time
      @{b}a@{ub}=acceleration

» v = u + at
» s = ut + ½at²
» s = vt - ½at²
» s = @{u}v + u@{uu} t
        2
» v²= u² + 2as

· Graphs:

» The gradient of a displacement-time graph gives the speed.

» The gradient of a velocity-time graph gives the acceleration.

» The area beneath a velocity-time graph gives the distance travelled.

· For projectiles, the horizontal and vertical components of velocity can be treated independently.  In the absence of air resistance, the horizontal component of velocity is constant while the vertical component of velocity downwards increases at a rate of 9.81 m/s²

· An object falling freely in air accelerates until a terminal velocity is reached.  At this velocity there is no acceleration because the force of air resistance, upwards, on the objects is equal and opposite to the weight of the object.
@endnode

@node Dyna "Foundation: Dynamics"

· @{"Mass" link PQU} is a scalar property of an object and does not change as it moves from place to place.  Mass is a measure of the reluctance of the object to accelerate.  It is measured in kilograms.

· Momentum is a vector, measured in Newton seconds (Ns) or kg m/s:

» Momentum = mass × velocity

· Newton's laws:

» Newton's first law:

If no resultant force acts on it, a body at rest will remain at rest, and a body moving with constant velocity will continue to move with the same constant velocity.

» Newton's second law:

The rate of change of momentum of an object is proportional to the total force applied to it.

» Newton's third law:

Every action has an equal and opposite reaction, of the same type and acting on a different object

· Newton's first two laws in equation form:

force = mass × acceleration
ft = mv-mu = impulse (in Ns)

· The law of conservation of momentum

» In a closed system, total momentum is conserved:
  > momentum before = momentum after

· In an elastic collision, both momentum and @{"kinetic energy" link WEP} are conserved.  In an inelastic collision, only momentum is conserved.
@endnode

@node Forces "Foundation: Forces"
· If the resultant force on an object is zero, then the object is in equilibrium:

»   up forces = down forces
» left forces = right forces
»   clockwise = anticlockwise

· The centre of gravity of an object is the point through which the entire weight of the object may be considered to act.

· Moments:

» The moment of a force = force × perpendicular distance of the pivot
                                  from the line of action of the force.

· A pair of equal and opposite forces not acting in the same straight line is called a @{i}couple@{ui}.

· The turning effet of a couple is called a @{i}torque@{ui}:

» The torque of a couple = one of the forces × perpendicular distance
                                               between the forces
@endnode

@node WEP "Foundation: Work, Energy and Power"
· Equation:

» Work done = force × distance moved, in Joules.

· Energy is the stored ability to do work.  Equations:

» Gravitational potential energy = mass × gravity × height = mgh

» Kinetic energy = ½ × mass × velocity² = ½mv²

· In an elastic @{"collision" link Dyna}, no kinetic energy is converted to other forms.
  In an inelastic collision, kinetic energy is converted.

· For a totally elastic collision:

» The relative velocity of approach = the relative velocity of separation

· Power is the rate of doing work:

» power = work done ÷ time = force × velocity

· The law of conservation of energy:

Energy cannot be created or destroyed, just changed from one form into another.

· Efficiency equation:

» Efficiency = @{u}   energy/power from the system    @{uu}
               energy/power supplied to the system

· The kilowatt hour is a convenient unit of energy, equal to a power of 1kW being used for 1 hour:

» 1 kWh = 3 600 000 J
@endnode

@node Wave "Foundation: Waves"
· Frequency (f, in hertz [Hz]): The number of vibrations per second.

· Wavelength (Ø @{"lambda" link MathX}, in metres [m]): The distance from any point on a wave to another exactly similar point (eg. crest to crest).

· Displacement (x, in metres [m]): The distance of a point on the wave from its undisturbed position.

· Amplitude (a, in metres [m]): The maximum displacement of any point on the wave from its undisturbed position.

· Periodic time (T, in seconds [s]): The time taken for one complete vibration.

» T = @{u}1@{uu}
      f

· National frequency of vibration depends on: size (smaller-higher), mass (lighter-higher) and stiffness (stiffer-higher).

· Mechanical waves require a medium to travel through.

· Progressive waves move through a material or vacuum.

· There are two types of waves: longitudinal and transverse:

Longitudinal waves have vibrations along the wave direction.
Transverse waves vibrate across the wave direction.

· The wave equation:

Wave speed = frequency × wavelength

· When a wave is reflected from a fixed boundary there is a phase change of 180°.

· Transverse waves can be polarised (the vibrations in one plane only)

· The laws of reflection:

» angle of incidence = angle of reflection

» The object, the point of reflection and the image all lie in the same plane.

· The refractive index (n) is the ratio of speed in free space to speed in the medium:

» free space ÷ medium
» real depth ÷ apparrent depth

· Snell's law of refraction:

i = angle of incidence, r = angle of refractive, n = refractive index.

» n = @{u}sin i@{uu}
      sin r

· The crical angle (C) is the angle of incidence for which the angle of refraction is 90°:

» Sin C = @{u}1@{uu}
          n

· For angles of incidence above the critical angle, total internal refraction occurs. (used in fibre optics)

