@node Elec "Foundation: Electricity"
· An electric current is a flow of charged particles (usually electrons).

· The coulomb (C) is the @{"SI unit" link PQU} of charge, Q.

· Current, I, is rate of flow of charge: 

» Charge = current × time ... Q=It

· The potential difference between two points is a measure of the difference in the energy electrons at these points, and is defined as the work done in moving a unit positive charge (+1C) from one point to the other.

· Resistance, R, is measured in ohms (§ "omega") is defined by the equation:

» R = @{u}V@{uu}
      I

· Kirchoff's first law:

The currents at a junction are conserved.  (or the current is split between the branches)

· In a series circuit, potential difference across each component = total p.d. and current is the same at all points in the circuit.

· In a parallel circuit, p.d. in each branch are equal, and currents in each branch add up to main current.

· Two resistors (R¹, R²) connected in series have total resistance (R):

» R = R¹ + R²

· Two resistors (R¹, R²) connected in parallel have total resistance (R):

» ¹/R = ¹/R¹ +  ¹/R²

· As the temperature of a metal increases, so does its resistance.

· Ohm's law:

» For a metal at a constant temperature, potential difference þ current.

· A thermistor is a device that exhibits a rapid change in resistance at a particular temperature.

· Resistivity is defined as the resistance of a sample of the material per metre length.

· The resistivity, @{i}P@{ui} ("rho"), of a material:

R = resistance of a sample, A = cross-sectional area, L = length

» @{i}P@{ui} = @{u}RA@{uu}
      L

Measured in Ohm Metres.

· The reciprocal of resistance is conductivity and is measured in ohm-¹m-¹.

· The work done, W, in moving a charge, Q across a potential difference V:

» W = QV

· Electrical power:

» P = VI

» P = @{u}V²@{uu}
      R

Power dissipated in a resistor:

» P = I²R

