@node Atom "Foundation: Atomic Structure"
· The alpha-particle (þ-particle) scattering experiment provides evidence for the existance of a small, positively charged nucleus at the centre of the atom.  The atom consists of a small, relatively heavy central nucleus composed of protons (with a positive charge +e) and neutrons (with no charge).  The nucleus is surrounded by a cloud of orbiting electrons (with a negative charge -e).  An atom is an electrically neutral particle.  »»@{"DIAGRAM" system Multiview AtomPic}««

· The number of protons and neutrons in the nucleus of an atom is called its @{i}nucleon/mass number@{ui} (A)

· The number of protons in the nucleus of an atom is called its @{i}proton number@{ui} (Z)

· The number of neutrons in the nucleus of an atom is called its @{i}neutron number@{ui} (N)

·The nucleon number is the sum of the proton number and neutron number:

» A = Z + N

· Isotopes are atoms of the same element (with the same proton number) but different neutron numbers.

· Different isotopes (or nuclides, if referring to the nucleus only) can be represented by the notation:

nucleon number                        A
               Element Symbol            Element Symbol
proton number                         Z
@endnode

