@node Super "Basic 1: Superposition of Waves"
· Waves are a periodic disturbance by which energy is transferred from place to place.

· When two or more waves coincide, we can deduce their net effect using the principle of superposition of waves.  The resultant disturbance at a point is found by adding up the separate disturbances of the individual waves.

· Constructive interference: Two waves arrive in phase at the same point

· Destructive interference: Two waves with same amplitude arrive at a point ½ a cycle out of phase.

· Stationary waves are established when two indentical waves travelling in opposite directions meet.  Usually this happens when one wave is a reflection of the other.

· A stationary wave has a characteristic pattern of nodes (no displacement) and anti-nodes (maximum displacement).

· The distance between nodes is ½ a wavelength

· Diffraction happens when waves arrive at a gap in the barrier, and spread into the space beyond.  The effect is greatest when the width of the gap is equal to the wavelength of the waves.

