@node ElecVolts "Basic 1: Electrical Voltages"
· A voltage is needed to push an electric current around a circuit

· The voltage provided by a battery or power supply is an electromotive force (e.m.f. "E")

· Electric charge is given energy by the e.m.f. of the supply; it loses energy as it passes through the potential difference (p.d.) across components in the circuit, given by:

» W (energy) = Q (charge) × V (potential difference)
» W = QE, where E is electromotive force

· A volt is a joule per coulomb.

· Because a source of e.m.f. has internal resistance, this must be included in calculations of current and voltage.

» V = E - Ir, where : @{b}V@{ub} is terminal p.d.
                      @{b}E@{ub} is e.m.f.
or V = E - lost volts @{b}I@{ub} is current
                      @{b}r@{ub} is internal resistance

· If you draw a graph of V against I:

» The gradient gives you -r (negative internal resistance)
» The y-intercept gives you E (e.m.f.)

· A potential divider uses two resistors or a variable resistor to provide a variable source of p.d.

» Vout = Vin @{u}  Rb   @{uu}
             Ra + Rb

