@node Cap "Basic 1: Capacitance"
· Capacitors are constructed from two metal sheets ('plates'), seperated by an insulating material, the dielectric.

· Capacitors store @{"charge" link elec}, proportional to the @{"potential difference" link ElecVolts} between the plates.  Capacitance (C) is the charge stored per unit of p.d.; a farad (F) is a coulomb per volt.

· Capacitance is how well a capacitor can store charge, defined by:

» Q = CV, in Farads (or C/V)

· The area under a current-time graph represents the charge stored.

· Capacitors store energy; the energy stored, W, at voltage V is:

» W = ½CV²

