@node ElecMag1 "Basic 1: Electromagnetism"
· Magnetic fields are produced by permanent magnets and by electric currents.  We can represent them by lines of force.

· The field of a current in a wire can be strengthened by forming it into a coil, and by adding a ferrous core.  This is the principle of electromagnets.

· Magnetic field is pictured as going from north to south

· The north pole of a solenoid, and the magnetic field around a straight wire can be found using the right-hand grip rule:

» solenoid - Thumb:   North
             Fingers: Current

» wire -     Thumb:   Current
                      Magnetic field

· When a current flows across a magnetic field, there is an interaction between the two fields.

· The direction of the resulting force is given by Fleming's left hand rule:

» With thumb, first finger and second finger at right angles, point each in the direction of the following:

@{b}F@{ub}irst Finger  - (Magnetic) Field
Se@{b}c@{ub}ond Finger - Current
Thu@{b}m@{ub}b         - Motion

The third finger will show the unknown direction.

· The convention for showing current going into the page is a cross in a circle.  For current coming out of the page, it is a dot in a circle.

