@node Phase "Basic 1: Phases of Matter"
· Matter can exist in three phases: solid, liquid and gas.

· They are characterised by the spacing, ordering and motion of the molecules:

» Solid:  Close together, ordered, moving very slowly/vibrating
» Liquid: Further apart, less ordered, moving slowly
» Gas:    Very far apart, no order, moving fast.

· The kinetic model of matter allows us to explaing macroscopic properties (eg. density, pressure, specific heat and latent heat) in terms of the behaviour of the molecules:

» Matter is made up of tiny particles
» These particle tend to attract each other
» The particles tend to move about

· @{i}P@{ui} = M/V, in kg/m³ (1000 kg/m³ = 1 g/m³)

(Density = mass ÷ volume)

· Pressure = Force ÷ Area (p=F/A), in N/m² or Pascals (Pa)

· The pressure in a fluid is given by:

» p=@{i}P@{ui}gh

(pressure = density × gravity × height)

Measured in Pascals (Pa), 1 Pa = 1 N/m²

· The specific heat capacity c of a substance is the energy required to raise the temperature of 1 kg by 1°C

· The energy transferred in raising the temperature of a substance is given by:

» E = mc@{u}^@{uu}¤

(Energy = mass × specific heat capacity × temperature change)

· The specific latent heat @{b}L@{ub} of a substance is the energy required to change the state of 1 kg of the substance.

· The energy transferred in changing the state of a substance is given by:

» E = mL

(Energy = mass × specific latent heat)

· Archimedes' principle:

» Upthrust is equal to the weight of water displaced.

· Upthrust = force on lower surface - force on upper surface

» A@{i}P@{ui}g(h2-h1)
