@node Deform "Basic 1: Deforming Solids"
· For a spring, a graph of load against extension (x) is a straight line up to the elastic limit (Hooke's law).

» F=kx (Fþx)

· k is the spring constant: the force required to stretch the spring by a metre.

· Stress is the load per cross-sectional area of a wire

» stress = load ÷ cross-sectional area, in Pa

· Strain is the fractional increase in the length of a wire

» strain = extension ÷ original length, ratio sometimes given as % (× 100)

· Young's modulus is the stiffness of a material:

» Young's modulus = stress ÷ strain, Pa

· Beyond the elastic (where the material returns to its original shape) limit, brittle materials break (they have a non-crystalline structure)

· Ductile materials show plastic behaviour and become permanently deformed (they have a crystalline (orderly) structure.)

· The behaviour of a material can be related to its underlying crystalline (@{"particles" link Atom} arranged in an orderly way) or amorphous (irregular) structure.

· The strain energy in a deformed material can be found from the area under the force-extension graph.

» strain energy (in J) = ½Fx
@endnode

@node Quantum "Basic 1: Quantum Physics"
· Electron diffraction can be explained by thinking of electrons as waves, instead of particles.

· Electrons behave as particles when they interact with matter.

· For light of frequency f, photons have energy hf, where h is the Planck constant: 6.63×10-³4

» E = hf

· The photoelectric effect: when UV rays hit a piece of metal at (or higher than) the @{i}threshold frequency@{ui}, it causes electrons to be ejected.

· A photon of light whose frequency equals the threshold frequency has just enough energy to release a weakly bound electron.  A more energetic photon may release a faster-moving electron.

· Line spectra arise for isolated atoms.  An electron moves from a higher energy level to a lower one, and the difference in energy is emitted as a photon.

· Other equations:

» hf = ø+Emax      where ø is the Work Function - ø=hfo
» hf = ø+½mv²max   (min. amount of energy required to release an electron)
» E = (hc)/Ø, where c is the wave speed
» Ø = h/p, where p is the momentum of the particle
@endnode

@node Nuclear "Basic 1: Nuclear Physics"
· Nuclear reactions can be represented by a balanced nuclear equations.  In any such reaction, the following quantities are conserved: @{"proton number Z" link Atom}, @{"nucleon number A" link Atom}, and (mass plus energy).

· In order to relate mass changes to energy changes, we use Einstein's equation.

» E = mc²

· Nuclear fission: A neutron collides with a atom, causing it to split

· Nuclear fussion: Two atoms combine

· The most stable atoms are the middle size

· The variation of binding energy per nucleon shows that energy is released when light nuclei undergo fusion and when heavier nuclei undergo fission, because these processes increase the binding energy per nucleon and hence result in more stable nuclides.
@endnode

@node Radio "Basic 1: Radioactivity"
· There are three types of ionising radiation produced by radioactive substances: @{"þ-particles" link Atom}, ß-particles and Y-rays.

Radiation   Symbol      Mass    Charge  Speed (m/s)     Distance/Stopped by
alpha       þ, 4/2He    4       +2e     slow (10^6)     3 cm/paper
beta        ß, ß-, e    1/1840  -e      fast (10^8)     30 cm/mm aluminium
gamma       Y, hf       0       0       light (3x10^8)  very far/m lead

· The most strongly ionising, and hence the least penetrating is þ.  The least strongly ionising is Y.

· The half-life t½ of a nuclide is the average time taken for half of the nuclei in a sample to decay.

· The probability that an individual nucleus will decay in a particular time interval is called the decay constant, Ø
eg. Ø = 0.2h-¹ (probability of decay in 1 hour)

· These two quantities are related by:

» Ø= - ln ½ ÷ (t½)

