@node Grav "Basic 2: Gravity"
· The force of gravity is an attractive force between any two objects because of their masses.

· We can describe the gravitational effect of an object in terms of the gravitational field around it.  The strength of the field at a point is the force exerted on unit mass placed in the field.

· Newton's law gives us the force between two masses (m¹ and m²):

G is the universal gravitational constant (6.67 × 10-¹¹ Nm²kg-²)

» F = -G @{u}m¹m²@{uu}
          r²

· Field strength at distance r from mass m:

» g = -G @{u}m @{uu}
         r²

· On or near the surface of the Earth, the field is uniform: g is approximately constant; its value is equal to the acceleration of free fall.

· An object in a gravitional field has gravitational potential energy.  The potential ø at a point in the field tells us the potential energy of unit mass placed at the point.  It is calculated from the work done in bringing unit mass from infinity (where ø=0) to the point.

» ø = -G @{u}m@{uu}
         r

· Another equation:  (Ep is gravitational potential energy)

» ø = @{u}Ep@{uu}
      m
@endnode

@node ElecField "Basic 2: Electrical Fields"
· An electric field is a field of force, and can be represented by field lines.

· Direction of field lines is positive (+) towards negative (-) or less positive.

· Field lines are closer together if there is larger @{"potential difference" link Elec}

· The strength of the field is the force acting on unit charge placed at a point in the field.

· The @{"potential" link Gravity} at a point is the @{"work done" link WEP} in bringing unit charge from infinity to that point.

· In a uniform field (eg. between two parallel charged plates) the force on a charge is the same at all points; the strength of the field is given by:

» E=-V/d

· A point charge gives rise to a speherical field; 

» field strength E=Q/(4ÐEod²)
» potential V=Q/(4ÐEod)

· These relationships are derived from coulomb's law for the force between two charged particles:

» F=Q¹Q²/(4ÐEod²)

· Field strength is numerically equal to the potential gradient at a point.

· Equation Summary:

F = Force               N
W = Potential Energy    J
E = Field Strength      NC-¹ or Vm-¹
V = Potential           V    or JC-¹
d = Distance            m
Eo= Permittivity of free space (8.85×10-¹² Fm-¹)

